    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-12-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-12-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="599"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d599">
                <head>599. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_JCE1" type="from">Charles E.
                        Johnson</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Special Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2"
                        type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d599fn1"
                        >Source: Johnson Library, National Security File, Country File, Africa,
                        Union of South, Vol. II, Memos and Miscellaneous, 11/64–9/66. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-12-23">December 23, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>South African Reactor Fuel Problem</item>
                </list>
                <p>Mac—</p>
                <p>It looks as though this problem is under control. <persName corresp="#p_HWA2"
                        >Harriman</persName> has talked with Foreign Minister <hi rend="italic"
                        >Muller</hi> and plans to talk further with him this afternoon along the
                    following lines: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>For obvious reasons we wish to delay shipment a reasonable time—about
                            two to three months—but we will honor our contractual obligation to
                            supply the fuel.</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>We expect the publicity on our shipment will be minimized.</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>We wish to apply <gloss target="#t_IAEA1">IAEA</gloss> safeguards to
                            the South African nuclear program and we would like to do this even
                            before the present agreement expires in 1967. (The present agreement
                            provides that <gloss target="#t_IAEA1">IAEA</gloss> controls will be
                            accepted at the end of the agreement or the agreement will not be
                            extended.)</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName> seems confident that Muller will
                    go long with at least the first two points, which will get us past our immediate
                    political problem.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName> had also been considering the
                    possibility of having the <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> supply the enriched
                    uranium. Following a meeting this morning, he has discarded this idea.</p>
                <p>This note covers both Bob’s activities and mine.<note n="2" xml:id="d599fn2">A
                        notation in <persName corresp="#p_BMG2">Bundy</persName>’s handwriting in
                        the margin reads: “Good.”</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">CEJ</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
